<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The sequence for the COI gene is 0% divergent from a sequence of a specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pante &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2011" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysogorgia abludo" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="abludo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chrysogorgia abludo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Pante &amp; Watling, 2011 (specimen NAS102-3, GenBank accession number GQ180138) collected at Nashville Seamount, New England Seamounts at 2246 m depth (Station 102; 
<geoCoordinate degrees="34.5828" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="5" value="34.5828">34.5828°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="56.8433" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="5" value="-56.8433">56.8433°W</geoCoordinate>
) included as comparative material during the species description (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0025315411001354" author="Pante, E" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="911 - 927" refId="B76" refString="Pante, E, Watling, L, 2011. Chrysogorgia from the New England and Corner Seamounts: Atlantic-Pacific connections. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom 92 (5): 911 - 927, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1017/S0025315411001354" title="Chrysogorgia from the New England and Corner Seamounts: Atlantic-Pacific connections." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S0025315411001354" volume="92" year="2011">Pante and Watling 2011</bibRefCitation>
). In octocorals, it has been found that COI evolves very slowly and therefore it is not suitable for species discrimination, with different species having the same haplotype (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1755-0998.2010.02875.x" author="McFadden, CS" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Ecology Resources" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="19 - 31" refId="B64" refString="McFadden, CS, Benayahu, Y, Pante, E, Thoma, JN, Nevarez, PA, France, SC, 2011. Limitations of mitochondrial gene barcoding in Octocorallia. Molecular Ecology Resources 11 (1): 19 - 31, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1755-0998.2010.02875.x" title="Limitations of mitochondrial gene barcoding in Octocorallia." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1755-0998.2010.02875.x" volume="11" year="2011">McFadden et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pante &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2011" class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysogorgia abludo" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="abludo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chrysogorgia abludo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the Atlantic Ocean, and morphological characters of the specimen collected in this study differ from the original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. abludo" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="abludo">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. abludo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as well as other species within the genus and hence considered a potentially new species In the phylogenetic tree (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Rooted Bayesian phylogeny of Octocorallia. Concatenated (16 S, COI, mtMutS, NADH 2) median consensus BEAST tree with posterior probability (PP) and bootstrap (BS) values indicated. Only values of PP&gt; 0.70 and BS&gt; 50 are shown, with values of PP&gt; 0.95 and BS&gt; 90 indicated with a circle. Nodes not recovered on the RAxML tree are indicated with a hyphen. Sequences generated in this study are highlighted in violet." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure15" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716341" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">15</figureCitation>
) the specimen was also recovered along with another specimen of 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysogorgia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, supporting its placement within the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
No similar 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="order">Alcyonacea</taxonomicName>
morphotypes have been catalogued so far from seabed imagery in the eastern CCZ or in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ. Consequently, the in situ image of 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysogorgia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. CCZ_112 was catalogued as a new morphotype (i.e., 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Chrysogorgiidae " genus="Chrysogorgia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chrysogorgia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Chrysogorgia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. indet., ALC_017).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The specimen was attached to polymetallic crust on the slope of a seamount in the APEI 4, at 4124 m depth.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Mopseidae</taxonomicName>
Gray, 1870
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
