<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Both 16S (0.3% K2P) and COI (0.6% K2) sequences are very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Mopseinae">Mopseinae</taxonomicName>
sp. NHM_330 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e9277" author="Dahlgren, TG" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Marine Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B20" refString="Dahlgren, TG, Wiklund, H, Rabone, M, Amon, DJ, Ikebe, C, Watling, L, Smith, CR, Glover, AG, 2016. Abyssal fauna of the UK-1 polymetallic nodule exploration area, Clarion-Clipperton Zone, central Pacific Ocean: Cnidaria. Biodiversity Data Journal 4: e9277. https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e9277" title="Abyssal fauna of the UK- 1 polymetallic nodule exploration area, Clarion-Clipperton Zone, central Pacific Ocean: Cnidaria. Biodiversity Data Journal 4: e 9277." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.4.e9277" year="2016">Dahlgren et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
), which morphologically resembles the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Primnoisis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Primnoisis" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Primnoisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimen from the western CCZ likely belongs to the same genus but based on genetic and morphological differences represents a different species from that of the eastern CCZ.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</emphasis>
The specimen was found attached to a nodule in abyssal sediments of APEI 4 at 5018 m depth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</emphasis>
No similar 
<taxonomicName class="Anthozoa" genus="Primnoisis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="order">Alcyonacea</taxonomicName>
morphotypes had been catalogued so far from seabed imagery in the eastern CCZ or in abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ. Consequently, the in situ image of CCZ_088 was catalogued as a new morphotype (i.e., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Mopseidae</taxonomicName>
gen. indet., ALC_018). However, it is often not possible to determine whether such small and abundant polyps are arranged in pairs or not, or the actual orientation of these with regards to the axis from seabed images.
</paragraph>
